                         Description Of Startrek Game
    The Game:

         As commander of the united starship Enterprise, your mission  is
    to  destroy  the  invading  force of Klingon Battle Cruisers within a
    specified amount of "time" known  as  stardates.   The  Klingons  are
    distributed  throughout the galaxy and must be hunted down.  Though a
    Klingon Battle Cruiser is  no  match  for  the  powerful  Enterprise,
    several  Klingons  together  can  weaken or destroy it.  In addition,
    natural hazards can damage portions of the Enterprise's equipment.

    The Galaxy:

         The starship Enterprise travels through an  N  by  N  galaxy  of
    quadrants  in search of Klingon Battle Cruisers to destroy.  The size
    of the galaxy is determined by the player's answer to the question:
              What size galaxy do you wish to defend?(1 to 14)
    A response of 4, for  instance,  would  cause  the  galaxy  to  be  4
    quadrants wide and 4 quadrants long.  The quadrants are numbered from
    top to bottom and from left to right beginning with quadrant 1 - 1  .
    Each  game  may  be  played with a different sized galaxy.  Generally
    speaking, a smaller galaxy size will make for a faster  game  because
    of the fewer number of Klingons and fewer stardates available.

    The Quadrant:

         A quadrant is made up of 64 sectors in an 8 by 8 pattern.   Each
    sector  may  be  empty  or  may  be  occupied by a Klingon, a klingon
    flagship, a starbase, a star, or the  Enterprise.   The  sectors  are
    numbered  in  the same way as the quadrants (i.e.  sector 5 - 3 would
    be the third from the left in the fifth row).

    Devices:

    Warp Engines:

           Course = an integer  number  of  degrees  clockwise  from  the
                    standard y axis.
      Warp Factor = a real number from 0.  to 20.  The distance  traveled
                    (in  sectors) for a given warp factor is equal to the
                    integer part of (8 times the warp factor).

              Examples:

       Warp     .2 = Enterprise Travels  1  sector.
        "       .5 =     "         "     4  sectors.
        "      1.0 =     "         "     1  quadrant.
        "      2.0 =     "         "     2 quadrants.

    Another example: If you travel from quadrant 3 -  1  in  direction  0
    (upward)  at warp 2., you would end up in quadrant 1 - 1.  Of course,
    moving in a non-horizontal, non-vertical direction will  require  you
    to  calculate  the  distance to be moved according to the Pythagorean









