    not resupply probes.  Once the inital supply of probes is used up, no
    more will be available.

    Computer Galaxy Map:

         The Enterprise computer can print a  map  of  the  galaxy,  with
    current   information   on   any  quadrant  the  ship  has  occupied.
    Information about each known quadrant will appear as  a  three  digit
    number  as  it  does  for  the  long  range sensors.  Totally unknown
    quadrants will appear as "...".  Quadrants through which a probe  has
    passed  will  appear as a minus number or zero repesenting the number
    of "objects" found by the probe.

    Questioning The Battle Computer:

         When asked, the Enterprise battle computer will compute
     1) Course for engines and super long range probes,
     2) Warp speed for engines,
     3) Course for a single torpedo,
     4) Average  phaser  energy  required  to  destroy  Klingons  in  the
         quadrant that can be hit, and
     5) Course and number of torpedoes for a dispersal  pattern  (Torpedo
         spread)

         The battle computer will first ask for the  coordinates  of  the
    target quadrant.  This information will be used to compute the course
    and warp speed for engines and probes.  Next the battle computer will
    ask  for the coordimates of the target sector.  This information will
    be used to compute the phaser energy required and the optimum  course
    for  a  single  torpedo.   Then  the battle computer will compute the
    phaser energy required and the optimum course and number of torpedoes
    to be fired for a dispersal pattern.  If certain devices are damaged,
    one or both of the questions may not be asked and  some  computations
    may not be made.  Warning: Once the battle computer has been used, it
    will apply its information to the next command  entered  and  execute
    that  command  without  requesting  any  additional information.  The
    commands which will be executed in this manner:0, 3, 4, 11,  and  14.
    Only  the command which immediately follows the request to the battle
    computer will be executed automatically, so entering any command  not
    in  the  preceeding  list will prevent automatic execution of further
    commands.  Note: The battle computer does not  always  calculate  the
    optimum  torpedo spread.  What it does calculate will generally work,
    however.  When asking the battle computer to calculate the amount  of
    phaser  power  or  the  best course for a photon torpedo just enter a
    comma (,) to the first question and  the  current  quadrant  will  be
    assumed.

    Other Features:

         If for some reason you do not wish to  finish  a  game  until  a
    later  date,  you  may save the game (via command 15) on a disk file.
    The game will be stored on a file where  the  name  of  the  file  is
    specified  by  the  player.   When you wish to finish the saved game,









